<TEXT>
vietnam told britain that it rejects 
the forced repatriation of refugees from hong kong and reserved the 
right to send them back to the british colony official vietnamese 
media reported friday 
a foreign ministry official handed a note on the issue to 
british ambassador to hanoi emrys davies said a vietnam news 
agency report in bangkok 
a group of 51 vietnamese were flown from hong kong to hanoi on 
tuesday in the first repatriation of boat people against their will 
however vietnamese authorities accepted the group back and the 
official media said without clear explanation that the repatriation 
was part of the framework of vietnams policy of rejecting 
forced repatriation 
according to the vietnam news agency the foreign ministry note 
strongly affirmed the policy of rejecting forced repatriation and 
and only accepting those who volunteer to return or who are not 
opposed to the repatriation 
it said the ministry official cautioned davies that any 
violation of these principles may hamper and even completely 
disrupt the process of cooperation to resolve this problem step by 
step as agreed to at the multilateral conference on indochinese 
refugees held in geneva in june 
the agency said the ministry official stressed that if vietnam 
discovers any case of forced repatriation it reserves the right 
to return them to hong kong 
many of the 44000 vietnamese who have sailed into hong kong 
since june 1988 are considered illegal economic migrants unless 
they can prove they fled their communist homeland fearing 
persecution 
thousands have held demonstrations to protest the decision by 
britain its colony to force the return of the refugees a decision 
condemned by the united states 
</TEXT>
