<TEXT>
college graduates in 1990 can look forward to a 
job market much like 1989s a year of good growth with 
engineering students pulling in the highest starting salaries 
according to an annual survey released thursday 
but the author of the survey said the 260 businesses surveyed 
were more cautious in their economic outlook than they were a year 
ago with 44 percent saying they expected business to be about the 
same and 6 percent predicting a decline fifty percent said they 
expected a slightly better business climate in 1990 
this is a rather unusual balance a decidedly mixed 
outlook said victor lindquist author of the northwestern 
university lindquistendicott report of 1990 
although there appears to be economic stability with limited 
growth there is vulnerability in the marketplace said 
lindquist associate dean and director of placement at the school 
if a decline in business becomes pronounced and widespread there 
will be an immediate and sudden drop in job opportunities for 
college graduates 
the 44th annual lindquistendicott report surveyed medium to 
large businesses and industrial companies among those surveyed 
were major employers in banking finance merchandising 
electronics and public utilities 
lindquist said there is a rather good match this year 
between the number of students entering the job market and the jobs 
available but he predicted by 1992 there will be more jobs than 
students because of a declining pool of students 
he said that on average starting salaries for this springs 
graduates would be up 39 percent over last spring lagging 
slightly behind inflation but he noted a new trend in which 24 
percent of businesses offered signing bonuses of about 3000 on 
average to students who actually accept jobs 
students with engineering degrees can expect to earn an average 
32304 starting salary the highest among their peers the report 
said those majoring in computer sciences and chemistry are not far 
behind with average starting salaries of 29100 and 29088 
respectively 
linquist said the outlook should continue to be strong for 
computer science majors 
accounting majors got the biggest percentage salary increase up 
58 percent over last years figure to an average of 27408 while 
starting salaries in salesmarketing showed the smallest increase 
up 2 percent to 27828 
lindquist said companies are spending more money recruiting at 
colleges and universities and noted a little bit of craziness 
in which some companies hold college receptions complete with 
caviar shrimp and exotic pates 
but he said companies continue to seek the old standbys good 
grades and extracurricular activities 
</TEXT>
