<TEXT>
from national hero to shunned exile to popular 
lawmaker andrei d sakharovs remarkable journey of conscience 
made him perhaps the worlds most celebrated dissident 
his life was a great irony the physicist who developed the 
soviet hydrogen bomb went on to become his nations greatest 
advocate of human rights at a time when the world lived under the 
shadow of nuclear war 
he spoke out for democracy when many others were silent he kept 
speaking out when it became fashionable under the reforms of 
president mikhail s gorbachev 
hours before he died at age 68 he stood on the floor of the 
soviet congress of peoples deputies and demanded that the 
squabbling opposition form an alternative party to the ruling 
communists 
we cannot take on ourselves responsibility for what the 
leadership is doing now he said speaking in an official forum 
the type of words that sent him into internal exile for six years 
that won him a nobel peace prize 
selfless brave and determined the stooped disheveled dean of 
soviet dissent lived to see many of his dreams come true his own 
people began to acknowledge his greatness as the rest of the world 
had done earlier 
but sakharov was never satisfied saluting reforms but faulting 
their inadequacy he constantly challenged even the man who turned 
many of his dreams into reality and set him free after nearly seven 
years in exile 
i personally respect mikhail sergeyevich gorbachev very much 
but it is dangerous to give so much power even to the initiator of 
perestroika sakharov boldly told the soviet congress in june 
after it added the presidency to gorbachevs job as communist party 
general secretary 
born the son of a physicist on may 21 1921 sakharovs early 
fame was not as a political activist but as a brilliant scientist 
he was inducted into the academy of sciences in 1953 at age 32 the 
hallowed halls youngest member ever 
in 1948 he joined physicist igor tamm in developing the 
hydrogen bomb and for the next 20 years lived and worked in 
secrecy with privileges that included a good apartment a driver 
a high salary and a government awards 
but like albert einstein sakharov began to worry about the 
morality of developing weapons of mass destruction he had his 
first major brush with top soviet officials in 1961 when he 
appealed to premier nikita s khrushchev to stop nuclear weapons 
tests 
khrushchev responded that scientists shouldnt meddle in 
politics two years later the soviet union agreed to such limits 
in a treaty with the united states 
sakharov horrified at soviet societys mistreatment of its own 
citizens once said his social and political views underwent a 
major evolution he risked his prestigious position and began 
using his influence for victims of human rights abuses in 1966 
speaking out for those who suffered under dictator josef stalins 
repressions 
the authorities showed their rage in 1968 when sakharovs 
progress coexistence and intellectual freedom was published 
abroad it called for sovietamerican detente well before the 
concept became part of soviet foreign policy saying progress in 
disarmament is impossible without human rights and political 
changes in the soviet union he was banned from work on secret 
projects 
sakharov called the essay a turning point in my life and two 
years later he helped found the moscow human rights committee in 
1971 after the death of his first wife he married yelena bonner 
a leningrad doctor and human rights activist who was to become his 
constant feisty companion 
in 1975 he won even greater world recognition and was awarded 
the nobel peace prize 
the soviets on the other hand condemned his strong criticism 
of the 1979 soviet invasion of afghanistan 
first they stripped him of his awards and then on jan 22 1980 
he was pickup up on a moscow street and banished to internal exile 
in gorky a closed city 200 miles east 
in an autobiographical statement written in 1981 sakharov 
reflected on his approach to human rights 
moral criteria in combination with unrestricted inquiry 
provide the only possible compass for these complex and 
contradictory problems today as always i believe in the 
power of reason and the human spirit sakharov wrote 
western governments scientific and human rights groups pressed 
the soviets to release him in december 1986 a phone was suddenly 
installed in sakharovs gorky apartment and gorbachev called to 
say he could return to moscow 
sakharov suppressing his joy at the news to show his concern 
for others told gorbachev to free all political prisoners 
two months after sakharovs release scores of political 
prisoners were freed and he threw his support behind gorbachev he 
gradually was rehabilitated getting his old job back at the 
academy of sciences speaking at official conferences and giving 
interviews to the soviet press 
in november 1988 he was allowed to travel abroad for the first 
time even though gorbachev himself had said earlier sakharov could 
not travel to other countries because he had access to state 
secrets 
although he professed not to aspire to politics sakharov was 
elected to represent the academy in the new congress academy 
leaders had initially rejected him but had to reverse the decision 
after a popular outcry 
sakharovs rumpled figure and highpitched voice became familiar 
to millions of soviets watching his televised appearances at the 
congress and fellow parliamentarian yeltsin called him the 
nations conscience 
age and poor health curtailed his human rights activities he 
looked far older than his years but when he felt he had to speak 
out he did such as his condemnation of the crackdown on 
prodemocracy demonstrators in china in june 1989 and constant 
complaints that gorbachevs economic and political reforms did not 
go far enough 
even though he was a poor speaker with a slight stutter and 
highpitched voice the public had come to know and like sakharov 
so much that an unscientific poll by a soviet newspaper in october 
1989 indicated he was the most popular parliamentarian outscoring 
even gorbachev and the maverick communist boris n yeltsin 
in a february 1989 tribute to sakharov the weekly magazine 
ogonyok praised a person who had earlier been cursed and 
published his longsuppressed essays and letters 
the soviet press had come a long way from the preglasnost days 
when it branded him a traitor and utterly ignorant person who 
groveled before the capitalist order 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

