<TEXT>
the food and drug administration is 
investigating reports that high doses of a generic drug used to 
treat leukemia patients may cause dangerous neurological side 
effects 
the fda said it is considering how to alert physicians to 
reports from the university of wisconsin that high doses of generic 
cytarabine made by quad pharmaceuticals of indianapolis may have 
more serious neurological side effects than are caused by low doses 
of the drug 
the reports were presented to the fdas oncologic drugs advisory 
committee on thursday at an emergency meeting called by the agency 
because of the serious nature of the problem 
stephen rinsler an fda pharmacologist estimated as many as 
3000 leukemia patients may be candidates for highdose cytarabine 
therapy about 30 times the normal dose 
an official said the concerns were not prompted by quads legal 
problems with the agencys generic drug division earlier this 
year the company and a former executive pleaded guilty to charges 
of bribing fda chemists to win approval of generic drug 
applications 
cytarabine is known to have neurological side effects including 
loss of muscular coordination and slurred speech but in high doses 
it appears these side effects may be more prevalent and more 
severe said dr gregory burke acting director of the fdas 
oncology division 
nothing is very definitive burke said its like a flag 
signal 
burke said the action the fda takes to alert physicians to the 
reports will depend on whether quad decides to take similar action 
on its own although he said some action will be taken within the 
week 
quad officials did not return a telephone call for comment late 
in the day thursday 
the fda investigation could not determine whether any patients 
had died as a result of the effects of the quad drug most of the 
patients being treated at the university of wisconsins medical 
center were on a combination of drugs were in advanced stages of 
the disease and could have had other side effects of the 
cytarabine which also suppresses bone marrow and damages the 
liver burke said 
burke said the fda was alerted to the possible problem by the 
university of wisconsin last summer the medical center returned to 
using upjohns brandname cytosar after the side effects of the 
quad product were noticed 
analyses of samples of the brand name and generic drugs found 
they both meet fda standards and neither drug appears to cause an 
unusually large number of neurological problems when used in normal 
doses burke said 
however burke said fda officials are concerned that when used 
in high doses impurities in the quad drug may worsen the side 
effects 
impurities resulting from the manufacturing process are 
different in the two drugs he said at high doses the relative 
amount of impurities could make a difference burke said 
the problem could extend to other drugs when they are used in 
high doses because all drugs contain a certain amount of 
impurities he said 
he noted doctors have found success in high anticancer drug 
dosages and because of that physicians are increasing dosages 
above the level for which the drug was approved in the case of 
cytarabine the high doses were about 30 times the regular dose 
burke said 
the fdas investigation of the wisconsin highdose patients 
found eight of 25 patients on the quad drug experienced 
neurological side effects while three of 34 patients on the upjohn 
drug had these effects rinsler said 
</TEXT>
