<TEXT>
underneath all the celebrity writer truman 
capote was a melancholy lonely little man 
thats one of the points playwright jay presson allen makes with 
surprising poignancy in tru her terrific oneman show based on 
the life of the wellknown literary personality 
the play which opened thursday night at broadways booth 
theater examines a specific highly publicized life but its 
lessons are universal allen takes the man and makes his plight 
moving capote defeated by too much high and low life becomes the 
victim of his success or rather the success he has cant 
compensate for the rejection he feels from family friends lovers 
and a fickle public 
in the play the pudgy pintsized capote prowls his plush 
apartment at united nations plaza he tattles on the telephone in 
search of a dirt fix talks into a tape recorder for a 
biographer and eventually ends up speaking directly to the audience 
about his strange unhappy life 
the show takes place in the week before christmas 1975 its a 
momentous time for capote just after esquire magazine published an 
excerpt from his novelinprogress answered prayers in it 
capote savages some of his rich female friends such people as 
babe paley and lady nancy keith much to his surprise and anger 
they cut him off youd think i killed the lindbergh baby he 
whines 
capote proclaims himself an artist and a true artist has no 
friends he says but the man still craves the acceptance of these 
people their abandonment hurts him just as much as when his own 
mother left him as a child with her sisters in alabama 
there are some sweet remembrances of that time including a 
reading from a christmas memory a heartbreaking holiday story 
about his childhood and his favorite aunt 
capote is played with astonishing fidelity by robert morse the 
actor best known as a brash musical comedy performer is a 
revelation and not only because of kevin haneys remarkable makeup 
which transforms him into a credible likeness of capote 
his capote is wickedly funny a sly imp ready to deliver an 
offcolor joke about the queen mum zing robert goulet or 
rhapsodize about the time he tapdanced for louis armstrong his 
voice is soft and sibilant his body language languid except when 
he dives into a dance bopping to the girl from ipanema 
but theres a desperate side to capote too and morse rises to 
the pain the playwright conjures up a devastating moment in act 2 
when capote puts his fist through a portrait of himself as a young 
man a beautiful golden boy who let his life fall apart it earns 
gasps from the audience 
allen deftly weaves biographical facts into the evening 
refusing to present capote as merely a case study the production 
which the playwright also directed rarely falters as it builds to 
the loneliest of christmas eves 
the luxurious apartment designed by david mitchell offers an 
appropriately panoramic view of the east river and the gaudy 
furnishings include capotes own sofa lent by joanne carson 
its an opulent colorful setting the perfect environment for 
allens extravagant colorful subject but capote who died in 
1984 probably would have been interesting wherever he was and so 
is the play tru is an affecting portrait of a gifted but 
peculiar writer whose saddest story turned out to be his own 
broadway critics praised morse in the oneman show they also 
applauded allen but wished that he had delved deeper into capotes 
persona 
clive barnes in the new york post called morses performance a 
tour de force and said that with the allens help capote really 
does live again 
the daily news howard kissel said allen captures both 
capotes wit and malice beautifully and that morses work is 
sheer joy 
it is a shock not to mention a pleasure and delight to 
stumble on capotes ghost in the unlikely person of robert morse 
said linda winer in todays new york newsday but she said allen 
unfortunately does not touch the mysteries of what made capote a 
great writer when he was up to it 
frank rich of the new york times wishing for a stronger play 
said in place of a life portrait with depth tru settles for 
its windup madame tussaudss caricature of the wrecked 1975 model 
capote and while applauding morses efforts he said his 
performances leaves one eager to see him in other works 
</TEXT>
