scotlands chief law officer today 
announced the first public inquiry into the bombing of pan am 
flight 103 which exploded over scotland and killed 270 people 
lord fraser the lord advocate said criminal prosecution was 
not imminent but that he still hoped to find the terrorists who 
planted the bomb in a suitcase that brought down the flight on dec 
21 1988 
the boeing 747 packed with christmas travelers heading to new 
york from frankfurt and london exploded over the scottish town of 
lockerbie killing all 259 people on board and 11 on the ground 
investigators displayed pictures at a news conference today 
showing how they had reconstructed the part of the plane where the 
explosion occurred with a gaping hole in the forward cargo section 
the department of transport said aircraft often are 
reconstructed but that this represented quite an achievement 
because it involved many small pieces scattered over a large area 
police had said earlier they had recovered 85 percent of the 
aircraft 
in a statement released at the news conference fraser said the 
fatal accident inquiry similar to a coroners inquest will be 
held next year but that a date and place had not been set 
the inquirys scope will include whether reasonable 
precautions might have avoided the tragedy and possible 
defects in any system that might have contributed to the 
deaths fraser said 
he said the announcment was made today to give authorities time 
to organize the inquiry and notify people and that it had nothing 
to do with the first anniversary of the crash next week 
fatal accident inquiries are conducted by a sheriff sitting 
without a jury the sheriff will issue a finding on the evidence 
fraser said the inquiry would have power under scottish law to 
order foreign evidence although it could not request people 
overseas to appear relatives of the victims are entitled to attend 
or be represented 
investigators remain determined to bring the evil perpetrators 
of this mass murder to justice fraser said this appalling 
terrorist outrage was an affront to civilized people 
everywhere 
there are two investigations already under way in britain the 
criminal probe headed by the dumfries and galloway constabulary and 
a crash probe by the department of transports air accident 
investigation branch neither of those investigations are being 
held in public 
george esson chief of the constabulary said his investigation 
had focused on the popular front for the liberation of 
palestinegeneral command or pflpgc an extremist palestinian 
group headed by ahmed jibril 
it would be right to say that we have focused our attention on 
one group but it would be unwise to rule out other 
possibilities he said 
asked whether that group was the pflpgc he said certainly 
investigators have said a bomb made of plastic explosive was 
packed in a toshiba radiocassette player and hidden in a suitcase 
which was loaded into a forward cargo hold they displayed a photo 
today showing the reconstructed metal container which held the 
suitcase bomb 
