<TEXT>
the nations high court today 
overturned convictions imposed in a controversial treason trial and 
set free five black activists three of them senior antiapartheid 
leaders jailed since 1985 
its fantastic because now justice has been vindicated 
said anglican archbishop desmond tutu when he and other supporters 
were told the five men were being flown from their island prison in 
cape town to johannesburg 
the three leaders of the united democratic front and one of 
their codefendants a church worker were convicted of treason in 
november 1988 after a threeyear trial their sentences ranged from 
six to 12 years 
the appeal court in bloemfontein overturned the verdicts of 
those four and seven codefendants convicted of terrorism one of 
the seven who was serving a fiveyear term was freed the others 
had received suspended sentences 
the appeal court accepted defense lawyers arguments that the 
trial judge kees van dijkhorst improperly dismissed one of the 
two legal experts assisting him in the trial 
van dijkhorst had said the law professor wa joubert was too 
sympathetic to the united democratic front because he had signed a 
udfsupported petition opposing a new constitition that entrenched 
racially segregated politics 
during the trial most of the defendants were granted bail 
but van dijkhorst repeatedly denied bail requests by the three 
leaders of the united democratic front a huge multiracial 
coalition formed in 1983 to campaign for black political rights 
lawyers for human rights an association of civil rights 
lawyers hailed the appeal court ruling as an excellent victory 
that would help restore the crebility of the south african 
judiciary 
the group called on the government to disclose how much it spent 
on this abortive prosecution which took years of blundering 
incompetence to achieve nothing but red faces 
ambassador ronald maclean of canada one of many countries which 
denounced the sentences said the appeal court ruling was the 
best christmas present imaginable 
van dijkhorst had ruled that the united democratic front was a 
revolutionary organization which incited violence in black 
townships in 1984 in a bid to render south africa ungovernable 
patrick lekota 41 the fronts publicity secretary was 
sentenced to 12 years in prison pope molefe 37 the fronts 
national secretary and moses chikane 41 secretary of the 
transvaal province branch were sentenced to 10 years the rev tom 
manthata 49 a church field worker was sentenced to six years 
the trial began in 1985 in the small farming town of delams and 
later was shifted to pretoria eleven of the original 22 defendants 
were acquitted at various stages 
the four men convicted of treason were imprisoned on robben 
island in cape towns harbor where many political and security 
prisoners have been held friends and relatives gathered at a ferry 
dock in cape town awaiting their arrival 
among the crowd was manthatas 5yearold daughter goitse who 
was crying with joy 
all four men are married and have children lekota and chikane 
each have daughters who were born after they were jailed in 1985 
and who have never seen their fathers as free men 
also on hand at the ferry landing was one of the defense 
attorneys david dyson he said the appeal court ruling appeared to 
be based solely on legal questions and doubted it was related to 
the changing political climate brought about by president fw de 
klerks easing of curbs on opposition activity 
the trial was one of the longest in south african history with 
439 days of court proceedings spread over more than three years 
the 368page indictment named more than 900 alleged 
coconspirators ranging from anglican archbishop desmond tutu to 
african national congress leader oliver tambo there were more than 
220 witnesses and the official court record contained about 30000 
pages 
van dijkhorst accepted the prosecutors allegations that the 
core of the united democratic fronts leadership was supported and 
guided by the outlawed anc the main antigovernment guerrilla 
movement 
