a county commissioner and three others were 
convicted of illegally making and selling equipment used to 
descramble paytv channels a case a defense attorney said was the 
first of its type in the nation 
dale county commissioner billy clyde herring and his brother 
bennie dean herring were convicted thursday of three counts each 
of conspiracy to manufacture assemble possess and sell video 
deciphers modified to receive scrambled television signals on 
premium pay channels without authorization 
the herring brothers and two others were convicted under a 1968 
federal wiretap law that was amended by congress in 1986 to include 
electronic communications 
defense attorneys george beck and jim parkman said their clients 
sold the devices openly and did not know the amended wiretap law 
applied to descrambling the defense contended the law was intended 
to apply to bugging devices not satellite transmission receivers 
a new federal law which went on the books in january 
specifically covers descrambling the four were charged with 
selling descrambling equipment in december 1987 and june 1988 
before the new antidescrambling law was passed 
beck said the prosecution was the first against descrambling of 
paytv channels using the federal wiretap law us attorney jim 
wilson could not confirm that but said it is one of the first 
