<TEXT>
i personally respect mikhail sergeyevich gorbachev very much 
but it is dangerous to give so much power even to the initiator of 
perestroika sakharov told the congress in june after it added 
the presidency to gorbachevs job as party general secretary 
he said he had no regrets about the difficult path he had 
followed 
i am proud of this exile in gorky like a medal i wear he 
told the congress 
sakharov was born may 21 1921 in moscow and like his father 
became a physicist he was inducted into the academy of sciences in 
1953 at age 32 the youngest member ever 
in 1948 he joined physicist igor tamm in developing the 
hydrogen bomb and for the next 20 years lived in secrecy with a 
good apartment driver high salary and government awards but 
like albert einstein sakharov began to worry about the morality of 
developing weapons of mass destruction 
he had his first major brush with the kremlin in 1961 when he 
appealed to premier nikita s khrushchev to stop testing nuclear 
weapons khrushchev responded that scientists shouldnt meddle in 
politics two years later the soviet union agreed to such limits 
in a treaty with the united states 
sakharov horrified at soviet societys mistreatment of its 
citizens said his social and political views underwent a major 
evolution he risked his status and began using his influence for 
victims of human rights abuses in 1966 
the authorities showed their rage in 1968 when sakharovs 
progress coexistence and intellectual freedom was published 
abroad it called for sovietamerican detente long before the 
concept became part of soviet foreign policy he was banned from 
work on secret projects 
sakharov called the essay a turning point in my life and two 
years later he helped found the moscow human rights committee 
after the 1968 death of his first wife klavdia he married bonner 
in 1971 and she became his constant companion 
he spoke out against repression of dissidents and for democratic 
reforms his cluttered onebedroom apartment became a mecca for 
troubled soviets crimean tatars volga germans political 
prisoners religious believers and refuseniks jews denied 
permission to emigrate 
in awarding him the peace prize in 1975 the nobel committee 
called him the conscience of contemporary mankind 
by 1980 the authorities had had enough sakharov condemned the 
soviet invasion of afghanistan in an american tv interview and on 
jan 22 1980 kgb agents seized him on a moscow street without 
charges or a trial he was exiled to gorky 250 miles east of the 
capital and stripped of his awards 
the oncerespected scientist spent nearly seven years in the 
remote city with kgb guards trailing him searching his apartment 
and secretly filming him he was cut off from the world 
despite heart trouble sakharov was drugged and tied to a bed 
and forcefed during a hunger strike 
we wont let you die but we will make you an invalid a 
doctor warned him 
western governments scientific and human rights groups pressed 
the soviets to release sakharov then in december 1986 gorbachev 
phoned to say he could return to moscow sakharov restraining his 
joy at the news to show his concern for others told gorbachev to 
free all political prisoners 
two months after sakharovs release scores of political 
prisoners were freed and he threw his support behind gorbachev he 
got his old job back at the academy of sciences and in november 
1988 was allowed to travel abroad for the first time even though 
gorbachev had said sakharov could not go to other countries because 
he knew state secrets 
survivors include a son and two daughters from his first 
marriage as well as bonners children from a previous marriage 
son alexei semyonov and daughter tatiana who is married to 
yefrem yankelevich 
