<TEXT>
the navy cant guarantee pilots wont drop 
bombs outside designated central nevada target ranges the military 
said friday as cleanup of stray bombs on public lands was suspended 
for the winter 
nobody could say that it wont happen again said olin 
briggs spokesman for the fallon naval air station theres 
malfunction of equipment that could happen and theres always 
human error 
capt rex rackowitz commanding officer at fallon where the 
nations fighter pilots train has said bombs and rockets might 
have landed outside fenced ranges for the past 30 years because of 
pilot or equipment error or he has said they could have skipped 
along the desert floor after failing to explode upon impact 
bombs duds and shrapnel that landed as much as one mile outside 
ranges were being removed or blown up on site in a sevenweek 
cleanup exercise codenamed operation ugly baby the ranges 
begin 60 miles east of reno 
there are plans to keep some 110000 acres surrounding the bravo 
16 17 and 19 ranges closed to the public through the winter in 
case undiscovered ordnance remains bureau of land management 
spokesman bob stewart said 
a team of 150 explosive ordnance disposal personnel flown to 
fallon to help with the exercise were going home friday briggs 
said there are no definite plans to enlist such a large group 
again to help clear away stray bombs he added 
it would be misleading to indicate we were finished with this 
thing briggs said well keep plugging away at it relying on 
the assets at our base but basically we only have five eods at 
fallon permanantly and they have to work on the ranges too 
briggs said he expects all the red flagged bombs to be destroyed 
friday so the navy doesnt leave ordnance exposed during the 
winter although people wont have access to the lands normally 
used for hiking hunting grazing and offroad vehicles 
the navy sought indefinite closure of the 110000 acres of land 
surrounding the bombing ranges because of fears buried ordnance 
remains undetected and could blow up if disturbed by people or 
animals 
the land will be reopened next summer and cant be permanantly 
closed without congressional approval stewart said 
no injuries have been reported from public contact with any 
stray bombs according to briggs who said the cleanup exercise went 
safely he said one navy worker hurt his leg when he fell down a 
hill but no other injuries were reported during the sweeps for 
bombs 
briggs didnt have statistics on the total amount of ordnance 
discovered during the exercise that cost the navy several hundred 
thousand dollars the navy recovered more than 2000 bombs and duds 
from its bravo 17 range alone 
the navy was cited by the state of nevada for improper disposal 
procedures of hazardous waste and for failing to notify the state 
of the cleanup effort that began secretly in october 
the navy faces fines of up to 10000 a day per violation if 
found guilty 
