bush had promised during the campaign to strive for a goal of 
no net loss of wetlands 
in a letter to bush on thursday the president of the national 
wildlife federation said the way in which the white house handles 
the epacorps agreement will demonstrate whether or not you are 
truly commited to a national wetland policy of no net loss 
there is no middle ground on this one its either up or 
down wrote jay hair 
the agreement has faced stiff criticism from the oil industry in 
alaska and the alaska congressional delegation who fear it could 
disrupt oil and gas production on the north slope and cripple that 
states economy gov steve cowper has threatened to sue if the 
agreement isnt changed 
many conservationists have grown increasingly concerned about 
the disappearance of wetlands such as swamps bogs marshes 
potholes on the great plains and tidal estuaries 
according to some estimates up to 400000 acres of wetlands per 
year have been lost in recent decades to housing devlopments 
farms shopping centers highways and other encroachments of a 
modern economy 
but wetlands buffer floods purify streams and provide wildlife 
habitat for many species that cant life elsewhere 
federal law requires that the corps grant a permit before 
developers may put fill in most wetlands epa may challenge the 
decision and has certain veto powers over it and the two agencies 
frequently had been at odds 
the corps agreed in the memorandum to strive to avoid adverse 
impacts and offset unavoidable adverse impacts to existing aquatic 
resources and for wetlands will strive to acheive a goal of no 
overall net loss of values and functions 
the epa in its statement said the memorandum does not define 
a no net loss policy but rather establishes a clear sequence of 
actions to be considered in the existing permitreview process 
under the agreement permit applicants would first have to seek 
alternatives to disturbing wetlands and if none were available 
would have to work to minimize damege to wetlands 
if the project would still cause significant harm the applicant 
would have to compensate for the loss perhaps by building new 
wetlands or restoring old already damaged areas 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

