the high court on friday threw 
out convictions imposed in the countrys longest treason trial and 
freed five black activists including three prominent 
antiapartheid leaders jailed since 1985 
scores of jubilant supporters including anglican archbishop 
desmond tutu welcomed the men as they passed through cape towns 
airport en route from robben island prison to their homes near 
johannesburg 
its a sign we are winning the struggle said tutu we 
knew that justice would prevail one day 
the three leaders of the united democratic front and one of 
their codefendants a church worker were convicted of treason in 
november 1988 after a threeyear trial they received sentences 
ranging from six to 12 years from a judge who contended the front 
sought to incite antigovernment violence 
the appeal court in bloemfontein overturned the verdicts against 
those four and seven codefendants convicted of terrorism six of 
the seven received suspended sentences but one muzi malindi was 
given a fiveyear term and sent to the robben island penitentiary 
malindi was a member of the vaal civic association an affiliate of 
the united democratic front 
