<TEXT>
us national income figured on the basis of 
population rose slightly in 1988 but was far outpaced by japan 
the world bank reported friday 
per capita income in the united states last year was 19780 
compared with 18580 in 1987 in japan the income rose from 
15840 to 21040 the world bank said the bank gave all incomes 
in us dollars 
the world bank arrives at its figures by dividing the value of a 
countrys total production the gross national product by its 
population per capita income thus includes people without income 
such as children and nonwage income such as returns on 
invstments 
the swiss continued to rank first in per capita income with a 
1988 average of 27260 up from 21310 in 1987 
mozambique ranked lowest among the 152 members of the world bank 
with a 1988 annual per capita income of 100 
the united states which in 1987 ranked second only to 
switzerland in per capita income was fifth last year behind 
switzerland japan iceland and norway the figure for iceland was 
20160 while in norway it was 20020 
much of the rise in the japanese income can be attributed to an 
increase in the value of the yen in comparison with the dollar as 
well as to increased japanese production elsewhere differences 
could be linked to shifts in the value of the dollar compared with 
other currencies the dollar has been rising in 1989 after a fall 
that began in 1985 
one former world bank economist who spoke on condition of 
anonymity cautioned that the figures should not be taken to 
reflect living standards 
in sweden people have to spend 15 percent of their income 
fighting the climate he said thats not the case in italy 
italys per capita income was 13320 for 1988 compared with 
10430 the previous year swedens was 19150 up from 15610 
the bank gives no figure on per capita income for the soviet 
union which is not a member country however the cia puts it at 
8850 well behind 12480 in east germany and 10140 in 
czechoslovakia 
china and india rank low on the list with an average income of 
less than a dollar a day 330 a year the per capita in the 
african countries of benin was 340 a year and 360 a year in kenya 
china reported the fastest growth rate 9 percent between 1986 
and 1988 while kenyas income grew by only 15 percent and benin 
declined 45 percent 
that does not take in account such illegal production as drugs 
and other goods made for the black market or wages that are 
unreported to avoid taxes it has been estimated that this 
underground economy can account for as much as a third of some 
countries incomes 
the world bank atlas 1989 also reported on some 
qualityoflife elements 
japan was at the top in life expectancy a japanese baby born in 
1988 could expect to live to age 78 compared with 77 for a swiss 
french or swedish baby 75 for a us baby 69 for a soviet and 42 
in such poor african countries as guinea or sierra leone 
literacy varied widely somalia niger and north yemen reported 
in 1985 the latest figures available that only 12 percent to 14 
percent of their people could read and write 
unesco reports that the literacy rate is 95 percent or higher in 
america the soviet union and the more prosperous countries of 
europe china reported a 69 percent literacy rate 
many poor countries have reported big jumps in school enrollment 
between 1970 and 1986 from 56 percent to 80 percent in china and 
from 7 percent to 50 percent in north yemen 
