ron silver stars as herman broder a polish jew who hid from the 
nazis during the war and now lives in brooklyn 
he is torn among his current wife yadwiga margaret sophie 
stein a polish peasant who took care of him while he hid from the 
nazis masha lena olin a fellow survivor with whom hes having a 
passionate affair and his first wife tamara angelica huston 
who has returned after supposedly being murdered by the nazis 
mazursky like singer and costagavras was never in the 
holocaust but enemies is simply a story based on secondhand 
knowledge and a firstrate imagination the director insisted 
isaac spoke to many survivors im sure who must have flooded 
the streets of new york said mazursky who also has directed 
harry and tonto an unmarried woman and down and out in 
beverly hills 
he probably got the story from talking to more than one 
survivor so that people like masha and her mother and herman and 
the person who hid him in the barn those are stories he probably 
heard and made this tale up 
i met many survivors had dinner conversations whatever all 
that i had gotten i gave to the actors while we rehearsed i had 
them meet with some of these people in los angeles and in new 
york 
for music box costagavras began with nonfiction and built 
a story around it 
in both films the holocaust is always present but never on 
screen unlike the recently released triumph of the spirit for 
mazursky and costagavras the subject seemed too large for even 
the most learned observer 
singer himself wrote from his hermans own experience with 
masha and other survivors of the german camps he knew that the 
whole truth would never be learned from those who had survived the 
concentration camps or the wandering through russia not because 
they lied but because it was impossible for them to tell it all 
so mazursky deferred to documentaries such as shoah and 
hotel terminus as more appropriate ways to learn directly about 
that tragedy once research was completed he concentrated on the 
actual film 
costagavras agreed saying he deliberately confined music 
box to the present 
you run the risk of being eaten by the story in music box 
theres no particular action no landscape its a very empty 
movie it takes place in the present but with people speaking 
about the past how you deal with the past thats the challenge 
with such explosive material it is important to have actors 
with whom the audience will be comfortable but balance is 
necessary the story always comes first as costagavras noted 
music box is not a jessica lange film any more than 
missing is a sissy spacek film or betrayed a debra 
winger film 
its not only being known its being a good actor he said 
youre a good actor and you get known thats the case with sissy 
or debra or jack lemmon and now jessica lange you can spoil the 
story with a big actor 
were far away from the actors of the 40s and the 50s gary 
cooper errol flynn this is over those kind of mythical stars 
now we go to see an actor playing a character a real character 
jessica made her character real 
mazursky praised silver acclaimed for his performance on stage 
in speedtheplow and said the actor was ideal for playing a 
herman 
a herman is somebody who comes from europe whose father was a 
rabbi whos a scholar an intellectual who loves women whos 
very bright ironic and whos sad the director explained 
ron can play that certain other actors a lot of them dont 
have all those qualities theyd have to find them im better off 
finding someone who already has them 
music box ends with lange shattered by what she has learned 
about her father embracing her son in back of their lakefront 
house with her own innocence gone forever she can only pass on 
her knowledge and help her son adjust 
the theme is about memory costagavras said of course 
the memory goes with the future she does what she does to save her 
son to have her son thinking differently and acting differently 
to learn how to live with this 
mazursky adds his own touch at the end of the film dissolving 
from a closeup of yadwigas baby to a shot of the coney island 
wonder wheel which can be viewed from hermans window the 
message is bittersweet wounds eventually heal a new generation is 
born but also the lessons of the holocaust may be forgotten 
out of the baby comes this image of the wheel mazursky 
said and all through the movie herman has focused on the wheel 
in his most contemplative and meditative moments when hes 
thinking about god knows what 
the wheel keeps turning life goes on the baby is life and 
life is mysterious theres man and theres woman it never ends 
even the holocaust is absorbed into that circle and the life will 
go on 
