<TEXT>
think big has been much more than just a 
slogan in wall streets bull market of the 1980s 
big deals in big stocks have engendered many a big profit but 
there wasnt much left over for investors in many newer smaller 
companies known collectively in the financial world as secondary 
stocks 
so on the verge of the 90s while owners of blue chips are 
wondering whether the market can keep on rising fans of small 
stocks are asking a more plaintive question is their turn ever 
going to come 
historically investors who take a chance on smaller stocks have 
been rewarded with better returns on average than those who opted 
for the presumed safety and stability of householdname companies 
wright investors service a bridgeport conn investment 
management firm says that sine 1950 small stocks have averaged a 
total annual return capital gains plus dividends 25 percentage 
points higher than their bigger counterparts as represented by 
standard amp poors 500stock composite index 
when the market began its long advance in the late summer of 
1982 that pattern seemed to be holding socalled junior 
growth stocks in technology and other businesses scored some of 
the standout gains in the first year of the bull market 
but around june 1983 they abruptly stalled and have failed to 
catch up 
during the last 6 years investor indifference to smallcap 
stocks has been virtually unrelenting wright analysts observed 
in a recent report 
since mid1983 they noted the sampp 500 has been rolling up an 
annual return of better than 15 percent a year over the same span 
the value line composite index of nearly 1700 stocks which gives 
greater weight to a broad array of smaller issues has posted an 
average annual gain of 69 percent 
that showing failed even to match the 72 percent annual return 
produced by threemonth treasury bills which are considered about 
the safest most conservative paper investment available 
so investors effectively got paid nothing for taking the 
considerable risks that come with smaller stocks 
many reasons have been cited for this seeming anomaly including 
the predominant influence in the market of investing institutions 
and foreign investors both those groups have a notorious 
predilection for bigname stocks with large numbers of shares 
outstanding and high visibility in the marketplace 
at the same time individual investors who represent a primary 
constituency of the smaller companies have been shunning 
investments in individual stocks opting instead for mutual funds 
or other choices far removed from the stock market 
it is axiomatic on wall street that no trend lasts forever and 
this one has gone on for a long time small stocks are now priced 
at attractive levels compared to the major market averages 
wright says 
despite their subpar showing in recent years the firm 
maintains small companies still hold an edge over bigger ones in 
their growth potential since they start from a smaller base and 
often are run in a more youthful venturesome spirit 
if a bear market develops wright cautions it is quite 
conceivable that neither big nor small stocks will be spared but 
the firm concludes that highquality junior blue chips are in 
good position to beat rather than trail the bigname stocks over 
the next five years 
</TEXT>
