<TEXT>
in a ruling favorable to the united 
states a world trade panel has ruled that european commission 
subsidies to soybean processors and producers impede trade a us 
official said friday 
the soybean case one of the main american disputes with the 
12nation european trade bloc had been portrayed as a test of 
whether ec agricultural subsidies generally violate international 
trade rules 
us trade representative carla hills said a panel set up under 
the general agreement on tariffs and trade gatt had ruled that 
the ec soybean subsidies violate gatt rules and impede trade 
the gatt panel was correct hills said we look forward to 
the ec correcting the problems that have been identified 
a gatt spokeswoman confirmed the panel had submitted a report on 
the dispute and said the parties had 10 days to react another gatt 
source confirmed the report which was not released publicly was 
favorable to the united states 
american soybean producers and exporters complained in 1987 that 
ec subsidies nullified or impaired concessions contained in a 1962 
trade agreement under that pact the ec allowed dutyfree imports 
of soybeans and other oilseeds in exchange for us tariff 
concessions 
the american soybean association has claimed that 15 billion 
in us exports have been affected by the ec subsidies policies 
ec officials were not immediately available for comment 
hills also criticized aspects of an ec proposal to reform 
agricultural trade under the latest round of gatt trade talks 
she said the ec proposal to rebalance its agricultural 
subsidies by reducing them on some products but increasing them on 
others would not prevent trade distortions and could reinforce 
them 
the us has proposed replacing agricultural subsidies with more 
visible and more easily removed tariffs that gradually could be 
reduced under gatt rules the ec has said it would accept some 
tariffs but oppose eliminating subsidies entirely 
hills is in brussels to participate in two days of talks led by 
secretary of state james baker the ec is the united states 
largest trade partner with 190 billion in twoway trade in 1988 
