eastman kodak co said friday that costs 
related to a restructuring announced this year would reduce fourth 
quarter earnings by 273 million significantly more than the 
company had predicted 
the 273 million charge brings kodaks total 1989 restructuring 
costs to 500 million or 850 million before taxes spokesman 
henry kaska said the photography giant had charged 227 million 
against its second quarter earnings 
kodak had estimated earlier this year that fourth quarter 
charges would be lower than those in the second quarter 
charges have evolved as plans have finalized kaska said 
its the difference between predictions and actual experience 
kodak has now accounted for all charges associated with the 
restructuring kaska said 
charges in 1990 should be only those that occur in the normal 
course of our ongoing operations he said 
kodak announced a restructuring plan in august designed to save 
the company 1 billion in costs and turn around its sagging 
profits the plan includes selling or reorganizing about 20 
businesses and cutting more than 4500 jobs about 3 percent of 
kodaks worldwide workforce as well as freezing wages and other 
costcutting measures 
this action reflects our efforts to sharpen the focus of the 
kodak organization by withdrawing from businesses and activities 
that do not contribute to shareowner value chairman and chief 
executive officer colby h chandler said 
our business units and support organizations are clearly 
concentrating on valueadding operations and activities he said 
as a result kodak will enter the new decade as a stronger more 
competitive company 
kodak earnings have declined in three straight quarters the 
rochesterbased company has blamed its poor showing on higher 
operating costs and no improvement in productivity as well as 
competition from abroad 
earnings dropped 25 percent in the third quarter to 329 
million or 102 a share vs 435 million or 135 per share in 
the same 1988 quarter 
earnings fell 23 percent in the first quarter and 85 percent in 
the second quarter when the first restructuring charges were 
recognized net earnings for the first three quarters were 589 
million or 182 a share down 46 percent from 109 billion or 
335 per share in the first three quarters of 1988 
mark obenzinger a stock analyst at trinity trading co in new 
york predicted that kodak would do no better than break even in 
the fourth quarter of 1989 
earnings in 1990 will improve simply because there will be no 
more charges he said but kodak will face a number of challenges 
to improving profits in the first half of the year 
among those challenges is the expected ruling on how much kodak 
will have to pay polaroid for violating its instant camera patent 
predicted to be in the 1 billion to 2 billion range the company 
also faces fierce foreign competition and a weak economy 
obenzinger said 
as you go into the first quarter of 1990 its going to be a 
fairly interesting time he said this addresses the ills of 
the past but does not guarantee them the future 
kaska said slightly more than a third of the 500 million charge 
reflects inventory writeoffs from the businesses kodak is exiting 
other costs include writeoffs of equipment and goodwill costs 
the amount a company pays for an asset in excess of its value and 
benefits paid to departing employees he said 
kodak has so far announced the sale of 10 businesses and kaska 
said the company hopes to have the sale of at least 10 more 
completed in the next two weeks 
