<DOCNO> AP891215-0298 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
debtridden circle k corp on friday reported 
that it has arranged shortterm debt relief in an attempt to get 
ahead of its interest payments 
company spokesman ray cox said the new agreement was made 
possible when a syndicate of banks waived compliance with the 
requiredprofitlevel covenants covering circle ks 325 million 
credit agreement the company has drawn on 260 million cox said 
in addition circle k received a 60 million 100day extension 
of credit he said 
cox also announced a 499 million loss amounting to 16 cents 
per share for the second quarter of its 1990 fiscal year 
in the aug 1oct 31 period circle k had revenues of 9372 
million cox said 
last year the company reported a 1330 million profit or 25 
cents per fully diluted share on sales of 85167 million 
part of the loss stemmed from a 22 million charge in the 
companys failed attempts to find a buyer for itself circle k 
began the effort in may and abandoned it several months ago after 
chairman karl eller decided not to bid on a buyout 
cox added that the operating results also included an aftertax 
loss of just over 1 million for its 50 percent share of a joint 
venture in the united kingdom 
coxs secretary said he was unavailable for comment on the 
status of the corporation which last month announced a 
restructuring that includes refinancing of debt a salary freeze 
layoffs and the sale of up to 590 stores deemed unprofitable 
on dec 7 circle 7 announced a dec 15 deadline to get ahead of 
its debt service with 20 million in credit 
it said the banks which are part of its revolvingcredit 
agreement agreed to make 10 million available and american 
financial corp circle ks largest stockholder agreed to advance 
the same amount 
the new agreement includes the banks american financial and 
certain issuers of letters of credit which have consented 
to refrain from taking actions to reduce their extensions of credit 
during the term of the shortterm agreement cox said in his 
statement 
the covenants apply to 200 million in senior secured notes due 
oct 15 1993 they require circle k to maintain at the end of each 
quarter a minimum fixedcoverage ratio for the preceding 12 months 
cox said 
funds to make such payment are not presently available to the 
company cox said 
he said failure to meet the profit levels or negotiate the 
agreement struck late friday would have forced the company to buy 
back 20 million of the longterm debt 
according to company figures circle k has longterm debt of 
about 11 billion up from 844 million the year before and paid 
96 million in interest and debt expenses during the 1989 fiscal 
year 
the companys financial woes followed explosive expansion which 
saw circle k grow from about 1000 convenience stores in 1984 to a 
high of 4685 the financial statement friday said the total had 
dropped to 4677 
the company owns about 12 percent of the stores the others are 
franchised 
</TEXT>
